  <!-- ═══ RISKS ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Robotics acceleration:</strong> Rapid adoption of the Hugo robotic-assisted surgery system could drive sustained mid-to-high single-digit revenue growth and margin expansion.</li>
    <li><strong>Spin-offs:</strong> Medtronic's plan to spin off or divest slower-growing segments (like patient monitoring and respiratory interventions) could accelerate total company revenue growth and improve focus.</li>
    <li><strong>Diabetes recovery:</strong> Significant improvements and FDA approvals in their diabetes care segment (like the MiniMed 780G) could restore market share lost to competitors.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>GLP-1 impact:</strong> Widespread adoption of weight-loss drugs (GLP-1s) could reduce the long-term addressable market for cardiovascular, bariatric, and diabetes devices.</li>
    <li><strong>Foreign exchange:</strong> As a global company, strong US dollar appreciation heavily suppresses reported revenues and earnings.</li>
    <li><strong>Supply chain & inflation:</strong> Persistent macro pressures can compress gross margins, a key driver for medical device profitability.</li>
    <li><strong>Debt load:</strong> While manageable, Medtronic carries over $25B in debt, limiting extreme financial flexibility in a high-rate environment.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is the growth rate only 5%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Medtronic is a massive, mature company generating over $30B in revenue. Moving the needle takes substantial innovation. Historically, organic revenue growth has hovered in the 3-5% range. Our model assumes steady execution without overly optimistic margin expansion.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why an 8% discount rate instead of 10%?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Healthcare tends to be non-cyclical; people need pacemakers regardless of the economy. Medtronic's beta is typically below 0.8, meaning the stock is less volatile than the broader market. This lower risk profile justifies a lower required rate of return (WACC).</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>What impact does the dividend have on this valuation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A DCF values the <em>entire cash flow stream</em> available to investors, regardless of whether management pays it out as dividends, repurchases shares, or reinvests it. Medtronic's strong dividend yield is a byproduct of the free cash flow we are valuing here.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

